<body>



<section>
    <h2>1. Introduction</h2>
    <p>
        Description of Data is a branch of statistics that deals with the collection,
        organization, presentation, and analysis of data. It helps in summarizing large
        data sets and understanding patterns and trends.
    </p>
</section>

<section>
    <h2>2. Data</h2>
    <p>
        Data refers to a collection of facts, figures, or observations collected for
        analysis. Data can be numerical or non-numerical and is the foundation of
        statistical analysis.
    </p>
</section>

<section>
    <h2>3. Types of Variables</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><b>Qualitative Variables:</b> Non-numerical data such as gender, color, or type.</li>
        <li><b>Quantitative Variables:</b> Numerical data such as height, weight, and marks.</li>
        <li><b>Discrete Variables:</b> Countable values (e.g., number of students).</li>
        <li><b>Continuous Variables:</b> Measurable values (e.g., time, temperature).</li>
    </ul>
</section>

<section>
    <h2>4. Mean</h2>
    <p>
        Mean is the arithmetic average of a set of values.
    </p>
    <p><b>Formula:</b> Mean = (Sum of observations) / (Number of observations)</p>
</section>

<section>
    <h2>5. Weighted Mean</h2>
    <p>
        Weighted mean is an average where each value has a specific weight according to
        its importance.
    </p>
    <p><b>Formula:</b> Weighted Mean = Σ(wx) / Σw</p>
</section>

<section>
    <h2>6. Median</h2>
    <p>
        Median is the middle value of a data set when the observations are arranged in
        ascending or descending order.
    </p>
</section>

<section>
    <h2>7. Mode</h2>
    <p>
        Mode is the value that occurs most frequently in the data set.
    </p>
</section>

<section>
    <h2>8. Quartiles</h2>
    <p>
        Quartiles divide the data into four equal parts.
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li><b>Q1:</b> First quartile (25% of data)</li>
        <li><b>Q2:</b> Second quartile (Median)</li>
        <li><b>Q3:</b> Third quartile (75% of data)</li>
    </ul>
</section>

<section>
    <h2>9. Variance</h2>
    <p>
        Variance measures how far each value in the data set is from the mean.
    </p>
    <p><b>Formula:</b> Variance = Σ(x − x̄)² / n</p>
</section>

<section>
    <h2>10. Coefficient of Variation</h2>
    <p>
        Coefficient of Variation (CV) measures relative variability in data.
    </p>
    <p><b>Formula:</b> CV = (Standard Deviation / Mean) × 100</p>
</section>

<section>
    <h2>11. Skewness</h2>
    <p>
        Skewness indicates the asymmetry of a data distribution.
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li>Positive Skewness: Right-skewed distribution</li>
        <li>Negative Skewness: Left-skewed distribution</li>
        <li>Zero Skewness: Symmetrical distribution</li>
    </ul>
</section>

<section>
    <h2>12. Histogram</h2>
    <p>
        A histogram is a graphical representation of frequency distribution using
        continuous bars.
    </p>
</section>

<section>
    <h2>13. Box Plot</h2>
    <p>
        A box plot is a visual representation of data using minimum, Q1, median, Q3,
        and maximum values.
    </p>
</section>

<section>
    <h2>Conclusion</h2>
    <p>
        Description of data plays an important role in statistics. It helps in
        understanding data behavior, comparing datasets, and making informed decisions.
    </p>
</section>

